bǝnaṅ cǝkap hamo siǝp dipikakolotan ṅaranna pinah iṅ buta raksasa, bǝnaṅ bobotoh, bǝnaṅ babalanjaan, hamo yogya dipikakolotan, ṅaranna vineh iṅ cipta ambara, heṅan pamere induṅ, pamere bapa, pamere paṅguruan, vǝnaṅ dipikakolotan, ṅaranna deva rumaksa di uraṅ, ladaṅ pǝpǝlakan vǝnaṅ dipikakolotan, ṅaranna ma ni bijil ti prǝtivi, ladaṅ hǝyǝk, ladaṅ cocooan, vǝnaṅ dipikakolotan, ṅaranna mirah tiba ti akasa.

22.

Noble and slave lineage

22.1

janma nu bǝṅhar teka nǝbus vadon, tǝ ñaho induṅ bapana, ulah dipikaritikan, bisi uraṅ kabava salah.

22.2

aya dǝi, ñaho di induṅ bapana, syaran saṅkan ahulun, lamun tvah induṅ bapana rampes keneh na janma, ṅaranna kapapanas ku tvah kolot, vǝnaṅ dipikaritikan, heṅan lamun ku carut ma ulah dipikalǝlǝhǝṅkǝn, ṅaranna janma midǝr iṅ naraka.

22.3

aya dǝi ma janma, ṅa, rampes(933) tvahna, rampes susukna, rampes vvitna, ulah ma tǝbus, heṅan ulah tuluy dipisomah, bisi hulun turunana, ulah mapajikǝn ka kulakadaṅ uraṅ, gǝs ma taña, bavakǝn sǝpahǝn sevaka ka uraṅ.

22.4

sakitu tata jaṅjavokanana pakǝn dapurna pulaṅ ka jatina dǝi, pakǝn(934) bǝtǝṅ diA31ri ti pañjara, pakǝn maur baṅsa uraṅ rampes, pakǝn bǝtǝṅ kapataka.

23.

Matchmaking

23.1

ini pakǝn uraṅ ṅajajadikǝn budak, ulah havara dipitotohkǝn mo ma nu(935) bǝnǝr bitan uraṅ, kareyaan uraṅ, lamun leṅkeṅ bapa turun ka anak lalaki, lamun leṅkeṅ induṅ turun ka anak vadon, lamun pahi ma ti pañca ti bumi ngaranna buta sumurup iṅ kali, hantǝ yogya mijodokeun bocah, bisi kabava salah, bisi kaparisǝdǝk nu ṅajadikǝn.

24.

Closing

24.1

samaṅkana kayatnakǝn talatah sang sadu, saur saṅ darma pitutur, mujarakǝn sabda saṅ rumuhun, turut tvah pakasabda, namo sivaya, namo(936) budaya, namo sidam jiva palipurna,

25.

Colophon

25.1

saṅ amaca maka suka, saṅ nurut ma ujar rahayu ngarǝgǝp cipta nirmala, yatna saṅ sevaka darma.

25.2

ini kavuvusan siksa kandaṅ karǝsian ṅaranya, ja na pustakanipun saṅ ṅarǝṅǝ pun.

25.3

mula manibakǝn sastra duk iṅ teja divasan, huvus iṅ vulan katiga pun, ini babar iṅ pustakanipun, nora catur sagara wulan.

^101 . mestri] A, mesti EdASD • The variation of readings is due to the problematic transciption of the character ṭā. In the Old West-Javanese manuscript corpus, this character can represent both ṭā or tra. Faced with the choice to read mesṭi or mestri, I prefer the latter, since it is the more common spelling in OS texts, i.e., Carita Parahyaṅan, Saṅ Hyaṅ Sasana Mahaguru, etc. Cf. Old Javanese metri.
